== Metanorma XML Style Warning

(XML Line 000258): Hanging paragraph in clause
	<clause id="_background_on_xri_and_si_lattice" obligation="normative"><title>Background on XRI and Si lattice</title><p id="_7cd78711-ce4e-4909-aceb-80e966bc1884">The technique of x-ray interferometry was first demonstrated by Bonse and Hart <eref type="inline" bibitemid="bonse" citeas="[6]"/> and Hart <eref type="inline" bibitemid="hart" citeas="[7]"/> proposed the concept of using x-ray interferometry for dimensional metrology.</p>
	<p id="_fdcfcb3e-24c1-4a7c-8568-2980d6d9538b">Until the 1990s, most x-ray interferometry work undertaken by metrology institutes was directed towards the measurements of the lattice parameter of silicon <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>220</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem> planes as part of a larger project with aim of determining the Avogadro constant in support of mass metrology <eref type="inline" bibitemid="windisch" citeas="[8]"/> <eref type="inline" bibitemid="seyfried" citeas="[9]"/>. In addition to measuring the lattice parameter, its variation as a function of impurity content has also been examined <eref type="inline" bibitemid="martin" citeas="[10]"/>. Several values for the Si <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>220</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem> lattice spacing have been published <eref type="inline" bibitemid="massa" citeas="[11]"/> and the <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>220</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem> lattice spacing appears in CODATA <eref type="inline" bibitemid="mohr" citeas="[5]"/>. More recently for the Avogadro project work has been directed towards measurements of the lattice parameter of <sup>28</sup>Si isotopes <eref type="inline" bibitemid="andreas" citeas="[12]"/>.</p>
	<clause id="_dimensional_metrology_experience" obligation="normative"><title>Dimensional Metrology Experience</title><p id="_810d4a2e-158d-451b-9b64-657eb43b7b18">By the early 1990s NPL, PTB and IMGC (now INRIM) recognized that Si <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><msub><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>220</mn></mrow></msub></math></stem> lattice spacing was sufficiently well known for it to be used as a reference standard for dimensional metrology using x-ray interferometry. They built a combined optical and x-ray interferometry (COXI) <eref type="inline" bibitemid="basile" citeas="[13]"/> facility at NPL for the calibration of displacement measuring transducers. This established traceability to the metre via both the laser frequency of a He-Ne laser and the lattice parameter of silicon which had previously been measured using x-ray interferometry. Long range measurements (up to <stem type="MathML"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML"><mo>±</mo><mn>1</mn><mo rspace="thickmathspace">⁢</mo><mrow xref="U_mm"><mi mathvariant="normal">mm</mi></mrow>
	
	
(XML Line 000263): Hanging paragraph in clause
	<clause id="_practical_implementation" obligation="normative"><title>Practical Implementation</title><clause id="_requirements_and_challenges" obligation="normative"><title>Requirements and Challenges</title><clause id="_operating_principle" obligation="normative"><title>Operating principle</title><p id="_c48d5c2e-7154-4e42-a889-046f438a002c">Silicon is the preferred choice for XRI construction, not only because of knowledge of the lattice parameter, but also because it is available as pure defect-free crystals in the form of rods in specific crystallographic orientations and is elastic. The demanding tolerance with which the components must be aligned has led to most interferometers having a monolithic construction being machined from a large single crystal, although a separated crystal system for long range AFM metrology is being jointly developed by NPL and PTB. <xref target="fig-2"/> shows a schematic diagram of the plan view of an x-ray interferometer together with the path traced by the x-rays.</p>
	<figure id="fig-2">
	<name>Plan view of a monolithic x-ray interferometer. B, M and A are lamellae.</name>
	<image src="data:image/png;base64," id="_1494d5e9-5827-45f6-8b6e-56aec3c74fed" mimetype="image/png" height="auto" width="auto"/>
	</figure>
