	<clause id="_requirements_and_challenges" obligation="normative"><title>Requirements and Challenges</title><clause id="_operating_principle" obligation="normative"><title>Operating principle</title><p id="_c48d5c2e-7154-4e42-a889-046f438a002c">Silicon is the preferred choice for XRI construction, not only because of knowledge of the lattice parameter, but also because it is available as pure defect-free crystals in the form of rods in specific crystallographic orientations and is elastic. The demanding tolerance with which the components must be aligned has led to most interferometers having a monolithic construction being machined from a large single crystal, although a separated crystal system for long range AFM metrology is being jointly developed by NPL and PTB. <xref target="fig-2"/> shows a schematic diagram of the plan view of an x-ray interferometer together with the path traced by the x-rays.</p>
